WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.880
We're on the brink of war with China for various reasons.

00:02.880 --> 00:04.800
I hope we make it to 2050.

00:04.800 --> 00:07.120
The demographics is as I describe it.

00:07.120 --> 00:10.320
And by the way, them losing doesn't make us winning.

00:10.320 --> 00:12.800
So I think you're in the part of the cycle

00:12.800 --> 00:14.880
where you've had the tightening

00:14.880 --> 00:17.760
and the dominoes are beginning to fall.

00:17.760 --> 00:20.640
And I think that that's going to produce more problems.

00:20.640 --> 00:22.800
The most important thing is to have

00:22.800 --> 00:26.320
this basic, well-diversified portfolio as important.

00:26.320 --> 00:32.000
Two years ago, you made some predictions

00:32.000 --> 00:35.280
about the future for America and the global economy.

00:35.840 --> 00:37.040
How accurate do you think you've been?

00:38.320 --> 00:41.280
Uncomfortably accurate, given the whole picture.

00:43.040 --> 00:46.400
It's like watching the movie over and over again.

00:47.360 --> 00:48.560
Maybe I should explain.

00:51.600 --> 00:55.200
For about 55 years, I've been a global macro investor

00:55.200 --> 00:59.040
and I learned that many of the things that surprised me

00:59.040 --> 01:01.520
never happened in my lifetime before.

01:01.520 --> 01:06.640
So when I would see certain things happen that were like that,

01:06.640 --> 01:11.280
I would go back in history and study prior periods.

01:11.280 --> 01:14.320
And studying, for example, the Great Depression

01:14.320 --> 01:17.840
allowed us to anticipate the financial crisis in 2008.

01:17.840 --> 01:22.880
Anyway, there are three big things that I observed happening

01:22.880 --> 01:26.560
that didn't happen in our lifetimes,

01:26.560 --> 01:30.320
but happened during the 1930 to 45 period.

01:30.320 --> 01:34.560
And they are the creation of enormous amounts of debt

01:35.120 --> 01:38.800
and the printing of money to pay for those debts

01:38.800 --> 01:43.680
and it having its economic effects on inflation and growth.

01:44.560 --> 01:47.920
The second is internal conflicts

01:48.800 --> 01:54.400
over the largest wealth gaps we had since then, values gaps.

01:55.680 --> 02:00.320
And the rise of populism of the right and the left,

02:01.760 --> 02:07.200
those conflicts, again, largest since that 1930 to 45 period.

02:07.920 --> 02:12.720
And then the rise of a great power,

02:13.680 --> 02:17.680
producing a great powers conflict internationally

02:18.880 --> 02:21.280
with the rise of China as a great power,

02:22.080 --> 02:25.200
challenging the United States and with Russia.

02:25.200 --> 02:29.440
So the great power conflict, that also is the most

02:29.440 --> 02:32.960
that that's happened since the Great Depression.

02:32.960 --> 02:37.280
So because those three things are happening now,

02:38.000 --> 02:43.040
and I didn't study them, I went back and I needed to study

02:43.040 --> 02:46.800
the cycles, what's happened over longer periods of time.

02:46.800 --> 02:51.040
So I studied the last 500 years because these big cycles

02:52.080 --> 02:56.800
take about 75 years and give or take about 50.

02:58.480 --> 03:02.000
And like the rise and decline of the British Empire,

03:02.000 --> 03:03.280
the rise and decline of the debt.

03:04.240 --> 03:09.920
And that dynamic I shared in the book, and I also shared it

03:09.920 --> 03:15.520
in an animated video, which is called The Changing World Order.

03:16.880 --> 03:19.600
And that creates a path.

03:19.600 --> 03:22.880
Now, it's not just because they repeat in this way,

03:23.440 --> 03:26.240
but one can see the cause-effect relationships

03:26.880 --> 03:28.080
that are happening.

03:28.080 --> 03:34.400
And so that has pretty much transpired according to script.

03:34.960 --> 03:39.680
We can get into those pieces, but I'd say those are the three main ones.

03:39.680 --> 03:42.880
There were two others that had big effect

03:42.880 --> 03:46.400
that I paid more attention to that I'll mention.

03:46.400 --> 03:52.000
One was acts of nature in the form of droughts, floods and pandemics.

03:52.880 --> 03:55.840
They were very disruptive when they happened, killed more people

03:55.840 --> 04:00.960
and toppled more empires or waters than others.

04:01.520 --> 04:04.400
And then also, of course, over a period of time,

04:04.400 --> 04:07.280
there's learning and producing new technologies

04:07.280 --> 04:09.440
that raises living standards.

04:09.440 --> 04:12.880
You know, it's raised per capita income life expectancy and so on.

04:12.880 --> 04:19.760
And so, but those five factors transpire in ways that we've seen before

04:19.760 --> 04:21.600
to create this big cycle.

04:22.160 --> 04:25.840
And if we can look at the cause-effect relationships,

04:27.440 --> 04:29.280
that's what I want to pass along.

04:29.280 --> 04:32.960
Because I'm 74 years old and I'm in a phase in my life

04:32.960 --> 04:35.520
that I want to pass along the things that are of value.

04:35.520 --> 04:37.120
And I think this is an important thing.

04:37.120 --> 04:39.760
But yes, it's transpiring according to script.

04:40.560 --> 04:42.960
Cassandra, yet again, unfortunately.

04:43.520 --> 04:47.040
What do you think is the likelihood of the meltdown of the dollar?

04:47.040 --> 04:49.040
Is America going to be wiped out at some point soon?

04:49.600 --> 04:56.480
I don't want, histrionics, you know, just, I don't want to overdo it.

04:56.480 --> 05:00.800
And I also don't want to just jump to conclusions.

05:01.600 --> 05:07.680
My goal here is to show people how the machine works,

05:07.680 --> 05:09.280
the cause-effect relationship.

05:09.280 --> 05:12.480
So I'm going to answer your question by explaining certain things.

05:12.480 --> 05:22.560
The dollar is held by countries in the form of debt.

05:22.560 --> 05:24.880
In other words, when you say, I'm holding the dollar,

05:26.160 --> 05:27.920
you're holding a debt instrument.

05:28.880 --> 05:32.960
And when we have a problem with the debt instrument,

05:33.520 --> 05:37.040
a few problems with it holding the debt instruments.

05:37.760 --> 05:40.800
And those problems are that, first of all,

05:41.520 --> 05:46.880
as a result of what the United States was in the world,

05:46.880 --> 05:51.920
the largest trading country, the dominant empire, and so on,

05:51.920 --> 05:59.840
there's been a huge accumulation of dollar denominated debt and dollars, therefore.

06:00.480 --> 06:06.640
And there's also been a lot of deficits that had to be funded,

06:06.640 --> 06:10.480
which happens by selling dollar denominated debt,

06:10.480 --> 06:14.080
which a lot of foreigners and banks and others bought.

06:14.800 --> 06:18.000
And so they have a lot of dollar denominated debt.

06:18.800 --> 06:24.640
Now, if you're a creditor, meaning an owner of dollar denominated debt,

06:25.360 --> 06:32.720
you need to have an interest rate that is high enough to more than compensate you for inflation.

06:33.520 --> 06:40.720
And so the production now of a lot more debt and them having a lot of debt,

06:41.360 --> 06:44.640
and then also sanctions internationally,

06:44.640 --> 06:48.160
which means freezing dollar denominated debt,

06:48.960 --> 06:54.960
all have created a reduction in the demand for dollar denominated debt.

06:55.600 --> 07:01.440
There's also concerns in the world about some of the things that are going on in the United States,

07:01.440 --> 07:04.960
and that's reduced that. As a result of that,

07:06.400 --> 07:11.120
you're seeing more transactions take place in other currencies.

07:11.840 --> 07:19.920
And if they take place in other currencies, then others want to save in those other currencies

07:21.120 --> 07:24.800
because that's how they pay for it. So if you want to save in what you pay for,

07:24.800 --> 07:31.600
you save more in it and less in dollars. And so that's the dynamic that is reducing

07:32.160 --> 07:40.080
the demand for dollars and dollar debt at the same time as the supply of it keeps coming,

07:40.080 --> 07:45.920
because we have large deficits. So the underlying value that those dollars

07:46.960 --> 07:51.440
represent isn't increasing, but the number of dollars spread across that is.

07:52.240 --> 07:57.600
Yeah, so that there's a supply-demand issue. That supply-demand issue, by the way,

07:58.160 --> 08:05.040
also exists in European currencies. Okay, they have too much debt and they're financed the same way.

08:05.760 --> 08:10.960
And Japanese currencies. And so what you're seeing is the movement,

08:12.400 --> 08:20.560
all that weight of money and debt is causing prices to go up, inflation. And that's also

08:20.560 --> 08:32.240
being worsened by the supply chain deteriorations that are due to the international conflict.

08:32.880 --> 08:41.120
So for example, in the case of, let's say China and the United States and other countries,

08:41.120 --> 08:48.400
as they prepare for the possibility of war, they want to be self-sufficient. And so

08:50.160 --> 08:58.000
as a result, they work on being self-sufficient more than integrated and efficient. And so

08:58.000 --> 09:04.400
that dynamic is playing an important role too. What do you think the next few years have got in

09:04.400 --> 09:14.720
store for us? Well, I'm going to take all three of those influences and answer it because they're

09:14.720 --> 09:24.320
all related. There's a business cycle or a short-term debt cycle, I call it,

09:25.200 --> 09:32.480
that sort of recession to recession and the way it works is you have a recession in weak economy,

09:32.480 --> 09:40.080
central banks stimulate credit growth, credit gives you buying power, you go out and buy,

09:40.080 --> 09:47.520
the economy picks up, and then that continues until you start to have inflation. Then they

09:47.520 --> 09:54.800
tighten monetary policy and then the economy weakens and it goes into the next recession.

09:55.600 --> 10:03.120
Since 1945, when the new world order began, in other words, we had the currency and also the

10:03.120 --> 10:10.240
American world order beginning in that, we've had 12 and a half of those cycles. They typically

10:10.240 --> 10:19.120
last about seven years, give or take about three. And so we are now about halfway through this cycle

10:19.120 --> 10:27.440
in which they did the stimulation, inflation rises, they tighten monetary policy,

10:27.440 --> 10:34.880
and we're in the phase of the cycle where there is going to be then the cracks occurring and the

10:34.960 --> 10:44.160
negative impact on economic activity and the like. And it's going to be more difficult than normal

10:44.160 --> 10:52.640
because there's so much debt outstanding and what we just talked about. So that is likely

10:53.840 --> 11:02.000
to happen over, let's say, the next year and a half, which means that it will take us

11:02.080 --> 11:08.160
in through the elections. And what we have is a situation where the second of those influences,

11:08.160 --> 11:17.600
the internal conflict influence, is bad and you have a lot of populism. So populists are people

11:17.600 --> 11:25.200
who will fight to win at all costs. They're not compromisers. I will fight and I will win for you

11:25.200 --> 11:34.960
and the rules be damned, compromising be damned. And so you're going to have a political situation

11:34.960 --> 11:40.080
in terms of that kind of environment. It's a bad time for that, but it'll end up

11:40.080 --> 11:48.640
paying an impact on the nature of the elections, I think. And then you have the international

11:48.640 --> 12:02.080
conflict. We are much closer to a big conflict, a war of sorts, either a sanctions and economic war

12:02.080 --> 12:09.760
or even possibly a military war with China. And because of the politics also, that that

12:09.760 --> 12:17.040
will be pushing its limits too because there are the one thing that most Americans are united on

12:17.040 --> 12:27.200
and both Democrats and Republicans are united on is anti-China. And as a result, and they all want

12:27.200 --> 12:35.600
a strong man or woman, strong person on that. And so I think you're going to see pushing of the limits

12:35.600 --> 12:44.720
there and that becomes a dangerous set of circumstances. So I think that if we take the next,

12:45.680 --> 12:51.920
you know, let's call it one, two, three years, I think that those are going to be riskier years.

12:52.640 --> 12:57.120
I spoke to an evolutionary psychologist and an evolutionary anthropologist a little while

12:57.120 --> 13:02.320
ago on the show and they were teaching me about the values and the type of characteristics that

13:02.320 --> 13:08.000
ancestral tribes would have preferred in leaders at different states. And in times of warfare,

13:08.000 --> 13:12.320
more dominant leaders were the ones that were preferred. In times of peace, more prestigious

13:12.320 --> 13:17.840
leaders were the ones that were preferred. Makes complete sense. If you are facing a scary tribe

13:17.840 --> 13:22.400
from the other valley, you want someone that's going to stand firm and is going to not take any

13:22.400 --> 13:27.040
shit and they're going to go for it. When times of peace, that person becomes a bit tyrannical.

13:27.040 --> 13:31.920
It's a little bit too much energy when there's not anybody else to fight. And it's so funny how

13:31.920 --> 13:38.720
you see this just same dynamic to me. It seems play out, no matter how big the populations get,

13:38.720 --> 13:46.720
it's essentially the same physics. That's right. It's happened repeatedly. If you're in a war,

13:46.720 --> 13:55.200
what you want is the commander and everybody to goddamn follow the instructions and just do what

13:55.200 --> 14:02.640
you're told. And it's not like we're going to sit there and argue, debate, and so on. So what you

14:02.640 --> 14:10.880
see is the breakdowns. And particularly, you see the breakdowns also when they're at odds.

14:10.880 --> 14:17.280
There's a lot more to argue about. Like now, the populace of the left and the populace of the right.

14:17.280 --> 14:26.320
And so in the 1930s, you saw four democracies become dictatorships. Choose to become dictatorships.

14:26.320 --> 14:33.680
They had parliaments that chose to become dictatorships. Germany, Italy, Spain, and Japan

14:34.240 --> 14:41.360
chose that because in order to fight, that's what you need. And your anthropologist friends are

14:42.480 --> 14:43.280
right on that.

14:43.280 --> 14:48.320
Yeah, they're consolidating power in an attempt to try and be able to enact more change more easily.

14:48.320 --> 14:52.160
It's not, we haven't got time. We haven't got time to get this across the line diplomatically. We

14:52.160 --> 14:55.200
haven't got time to get everybody on the same page. We'll have one person who knows what they're

14:55.200 --> 14:58.400
doing and they'll push it forward. One thing that I...

14:58.400 --> 15:07.760
And another thing that's common is the foreign enemy. When you have a situation where you have

15:07.760 --> 15:17.680
internal dispute, it's very, very common to try to bring the country together, get support by the

15:17.680 --> 15:27.040
leader by having the common enemy. And so we'll all rally around the leader and you could see...

15:28.480 --> 15:38.160
It was like when 9-11 happened and the president, Bush gets a standing ovation and we're all behind

15:38.160 --> 15:43.920
you in that fight. And so that's timeless and universal dynamic.

15:43.920 --> 15:49.120
If you can't bond yourselves together over shared love of an in-group, shared hatred of an out-group

15:49.120 --> 15:56.320
is a close enough proxy, I suppose, for that interim. Was there anything over the last two years

15:56.320 --> 16:01.760
that you didn't anticipate or is there anything particularly unique about the situation that

16:01.760 --> 16:08.720
we're in now? Every time people say it's going to be different this time. Is there anything that

16:08.720 --> 16:12.160
could make things different this time or is there anything that you've been surprised by?

16:14.400 --> 16:21.040
By and large, I haven't been surprised by... I mean, I didn't anticipate that we were going to have

16:21.040 --> 16:32.320
the war with Russia, but I did anticipate that we were likely headed in a war-like environment.

16:32.320 --> 16:42.160
It's very much fell with as expected there. The economic and the financial very much is the same.

16:42.480 --> 16:52.960
So I'd have to, by and large, almost exactly, it's transpired the way described. And that's why,

16:52.960 --> 17:00.640
again, look, I did the video for free on YouTube, the changing world order.

17:02.560 --> 17:08.640
What I'm trying to do is to just pass it along for people's consideration to understand the

17:08.640 --> 17:15.920
cause-effect relationship that goes there. But yes, it's unfortunately going according to script.

17:15.920 --> 17:23.920
That doesn't mean it's destined, but it's difficult to take off track. What do I mean by that?

17:27.520 --> 17:36.560
Each stage is the logical consequence of the stage that proceeded it. So let's take the

17:36.560 --> 17:47.840
existing situation. The United States has a lot of debt, and it has deficits. So it has to sell

17:47.840 --> 17:55.920
debt. Now, if you say, and others are holding debt, and if you say, how do you get healthy,

17:56.000 --> 18:09.040
you have to spend less than you earn to not borrow money and get financially strong.

18:10.800 --> 18:16.160
That's difficult, and particularly when you have a lot of debt, because you have to take a portion

18:16.160 --> 18:22.320
of your income and you have to pay the debt. And also you're living in spending more than

18:22.320 --> 18:28.320
you're earning. And so how do you rectify that? What? Cut spending? I mean, it's very difficult

18:28.320 --> 18:37.040
to cut spending. Or raise income? That's not easy. So cut spending? What do you cut? Okay.

18:37.040 --> 18:45.440
So we're living in a world now where policymakers don't think, how much money do I have to spend,

18:45.520 --> 18:56.480
and what should I prioritize it on? They think, how much money do I need to spend without regard

18:56.480 --> 19:04.800
to how much they have, and then they go spend it, and then they have deficits that central banks

19:04.800 --> 19:10.480
can print. It's just like the same as individuals. They have the deficit, but in their case,

19:10.480 --> 19:17.120
they have the capacity to print the money to pay the deficit. So it's not easy to fix the financial

19:17.120 --> 19:25.120
problem. The internal problem, you know what it's like. Can you get people to come together

19:25.920 --> 19:33.040
to say there's a common problem? Let's have the left and the right and people. Very difficult.

19:33.040 --> 19:42.080
People have big differences in values and conditions. And so it's very difficult to bring

19:42.080 --> 19:48.560
them together to deal with the problems. And the same is true internationally, you know?

19:48.560 --> 19:58.000
Easier said than done. So given that dynamic, there is then the stages. And so it's pretty clear

19:58.080 --> 20:06.320
normally what comes next. Given all of these changes, what do you think people can do

20:07.040 --> 20:10.720
to best prepare themselves financially for the next few years?

20:11.840 --> 20:25.360
Well, I think that in saving, let's talk about that, there is, I think of savings in

20:25.920 --> 20:34.640
tiers. The first tier is to secure your well-being, tone a portfolio of assets that are going to

20:35.440 --> 20:42.000
secure your well-being. And then after you have that taken care of, then you can go to the next

20:42.000 --> 20:50.720
level, take more risk and so on. That well-being, that purchasing power has to be viewed in terms of

20:50.720 --> 21:00.160
inflation-adjusted dollars. If you're holding a debt instrument and a cash-paying instrument,

21:00.160 --> 21:08.080
and it gives you a 2% interest and you have a 5% or 6% inflation, you lose money at 3% a year.

21:08.080 --> 21:15.680
So you have to look at that in real dollars. And you have to hold that portfolio in a way

21:16.640 --> 21:23.200
that is balanced to any kind of economic environment. And then the way I do it, and I

21:25.200 --> 21:31.920
remember I didn't have anything, and then I start to acquire money. And I start to think,

21:31.920 --> 21:42.800
okay, how many weeks do I have, months do I have, or years that I'm financially safe?

21:42.880 --> 21:48.400
And what do I hold it in? And then once you've got that taken care of, you can go beyond it.

21:49.760 --> 21:58.480
And I wanted it in a very well-balanced portfolio, that type of portfolio that does

21:58.480 --> 22:05.360
equally well, no matter what happens. I can explain that a little bit more if you want.

22:05.760 --> 22:16.480
That'd be good. Okay. There are basically two big influences on markets,

22:20.000 --> 22:31.040
the growth rate and the inflation rate. Like, if you know that growth is going to be

22:32.000 --> 22:38.960
faster than expected, and inflation is going to be higher than expected,

22:39.840 --> 22:48.720
you know that bonds are going to go down and vice versa. So the way I give that as an example,

22:50.960 --> 22:57.360
so the way I look at it is there are those two big influences, and then they can,

22:57.920 --> 23:01.520
four environments, and each one of them can go up or down. So there are four

23:03.360 --> 23:10.160
quadrants that I think of, rising growth, falling growth, rising inflation, and falling inflation.

23:10.960 --> 23:18.000
And I want to have a portfolio that will be 25% of my risk in each one of those,

23:18.640 --> 23:26.080
so that I don't have any bias. And so I pick the assets that are going to do well in each of those

23:26.080 --> 23:34.240
four quadrants, and I hold them in a balanced way. And I've tested that going back actually to 1900

23:34.240 --> 23:43.680
and so on, and you'll actually increase your buying power. And so that's the kind of thing

23:43.680 --> 23:50.560
that I think in the beginning. Then you have to also make provision for taxes to some extent.

23:51.120 --> 23:57.360
So I say whatever that amount of money is, I want twice as that. So in case it goes in half,

23:58.080 --> 24:05.200
and I want to build a portfolio that looks like that for, I don't know, X number of years,

24:05.200 --> 24:11.040
that I have that, and that's the safe savings. And then when I go beyond that, then I'll take

24:11.040 --> 24:18.960
more risk. But I think that being safe, particularly in this kind of an environment,

24:18.960 --> 24:25.600
is important. And I would take a perspective of how to do that. That's like the one I'm just

24:25.600 --> 24:30.880
describing. What would be an example of an investment for each of those four quadrants?

24:31.680 --> 24:37.280
Well, I'm worried that we're going to take a long time to explain it. I've explained it

24:37.520 --> 24:49.840
elsewhere. But let me give an example. I'll take it. If growth, so there's these four quadrants,

24:49.840 --> 24:58.560
growth and inflation. If growth is less than expected, and inflation is less than expected,

24:58.560 --> 25:07.440
you would like to own bonds. If it's higher than expected, you would not want to own bonds.

25:10.720 --> 25:19.920
If inflation is higher than expected, you would want to own assets such as commodities and gold

25:20.240 --> 25:34.560
and inflation index bonds. If growth is faster than expected, particularly if inflation is less

25:34.560 --> 25:41.040
than expected, you'd want to own stocks. So you get the idea.

